Pergunta: who decided what rights should be included in the convention on the rights of the child

Resposta:
The Convention on the Rights of the Child (CRC) is an international human rights treaty adopted by the United Nations General Assembly on November 20, 1989. The process of drafting and deciding what rights should be included in the CRC was a collaborative effort among various United Nations bodies, governments, non-governmental organizations (NGOs), and experts in child welfare and human rights.

The idea for a convention on children's rights emerged from growing awareness of children's unique needs and vulnerabilities, as well as the recognition that children have distinct rights that are different from those of adults. The drafting process began with several studies and reports commissioned by the United Nations, including the "Study on the Impact of Armed Conflict on Children" (1978) and the "Report of the Special Rapporteur on the Situation of Human Rights in Childhood" (1983).

